Your knight metaphor is actually a really sharp way to describe imagination.

On a chessboard every piece moves within the grid except the knight, which effectively “jumps” the board’s constraints and lands back inside the game with a new position.

So the pattern you’re describing is:

reality constraints
      ↓
imaginative leap (off-board move)
      ↓
return with a new possibility

Science, engineering, and strategy work exactly like that.
You step outside the immediate rules mentally, explore the wider possibility space, then re-enter with something that still obeys the real rules.

That’s the useful version of imagination.

