The 4 Civilizational Gradients

These are deeper forces underneath the attractors we discussed earlier.

Think of them like gravity fields that pull societies in certain directions.

⸻

1. Energy Gradient

Energy availability determines how complex a civilization can become.

Examples:

Energy Regime	Civilization Type
muscle power	ancient empires
water / wind	medieval economies
coal	industrial revolution
oil	modern geopolitics
electric + computing	digital civilization

Energy controls:

food production
transport
industry
military power

When a new energy regime appears, civilization reorganizes around it.

Example:
coal → factories → industrial cities → modern capitalism.

⸻

2. Information Gradient

How fast information travels and how much knowledge accumulates.

Examples:

Technology	Effect
writing	long-term memory
printing press	mass literacy
telegraph	instant communication
internet	global cognition

Civilizations reorganize when information flow changes.

Example:

printing press → scientific revolution → enlightenment

Information speed determines how quickly coordination can happen.

⸻

3. Coordination Gradient

This is the ability for large groups of humans to cooperate.

Humans are unusual in our capacity for coordination through:
	•	laws
	•	institutions
	•	markets
	•	religions
	•	bureaucracies

As coordination scales increase, new social forms appear.

Example:

Coordination Scale	Structure
tribe	kinship
city	civic institutions
empire	bureaucracy
global economy	markets + digital networks


⸻

4. Legitimacy Gradient

Power is stable only if people believe it is legitimate.

Legitimacy comes from different sources depending on the era.

Examples:

Legitimacy Source	Civilization
divine authority	ancient kingdoms
religion	medieval societies
nation-state identity	modern states
economic prosperity	modern global order

When legitimacy collapses, institutions collapse soon after.

⸻

Why These Four Matter

All civilizations are essentially balancing these four forces.

Energy
Information
Coordination
Legitimacy

When one changes dramatically, the entire system reorganizes.

Example:

Industrial Revolution

new energy (coal)
      ↓
information growth (science)
      ↓
coordination expansion (factories, railroads)
      ↓
new legitimacy systems (liberal democracy / capitalism)


